                    <h2 style="font-family: 'Fraunces', serif; margin-top: 40px; color: #141312;">2. Optimization Steps</h2>
                    <div style="margin-top: 20px;">
                        <div class="step-block">
                            <p style="color: #141312; line-height: 1.7;"><span class="step-num font-mono">01 /</span> <strong>Starch Suspension Build:</strong> Boil the spaghetti in a shallow pot with less water than normal. Restricting the total fluid volume forces a higher concentration of loose starches to shed from the pasta directly into the boiling liquid matrix, which acts as our crucial binding binder.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="step-block">
                            <p style="color: #141312; line-height: 1.7;"><span class="step-num font-mono">02 /</span> <strong>Low-Heat Infusion:</strong> Slice garlic cloves paper-thin. Cook them slowly in a pan alongside the oil and red pepper flakes over ultra-low heat. The goal is to deeply extract all garlic sulfur aromatics into the lipid pool without allowing the slices to crisp or pick up bitter, burnt qualities.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="step-block">
                            <p style="color: #141312; line-height: 1.7;"><span class="step-num font-mono">03 /</span> <strong>Mechanical Emulsification:</strong> Drag the under-cooked pasta straight into the garlic oil pan. Ladle in 100ml of your thick, starchy pasta boiling water. Swirl and shake the pan vigorously for 2 minutes—the intense mechanical motion forces the water starches and hot oils to fuse into a uniform, glossy glaze.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
